    "body": "The reason the transaction does not appear to revert is because setting a fixed gas limit means Geth will not perform gas estimation and therefore will not catch the revert before executing the transaction. Notably, the following test *does* pass against both normal geth and l2geth:\r\n\r\n```\r\nconst hre = require('hardhat')\r\nconst chai = require('chai')\r\nconst chaiAsPromised = require('chai-as-promised')\r\nconst expect = chai.expect\r\n\r\nchai.use(chaiAsPromised)\r\n\r\ndescribe('Reverter', () => {\r\n    it('should revert', async () => {\r\n        const factory = await hre.ethers.getContractFactory('Reverter')\r\n        const contract = await factory.deploy()\r\n\r\n        const result = await contract.doRevert({\r\n            gasLimit: 5000000\r\n        })\r\n        \r\n        await expect(\r\n            result.wait()    \r\n        ).to.be.rejectedWith('transaction failed')\r\n    })\r\n})\r\n```\r\n\r\nResult:\r\n\r\n```\r\n  Reverter\r\n    âœ“ should revert (127ms)\r\n\r\n\r\n  1 passing (129ms)\r\n```\r\n\r\nI hope this explains the issue. I'm going to close this for now. If you believe this is *not* the correct behavior of standard geth, please comment and I will reopen the issue.",
